<article>
    <h1>What global fi&#xAD;nan&#xAD;cial cen&#xAD;tres can do to sup&#xAD;port a green re&#xAD;cov&#xAD;ery</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200715/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-15"><time>2020-07-15</time></a>
        - <span>OPINION</span>
        - <span role="byline">Wil&#xAD;liam Russell For The Straits Times stopin&#xAD;ion@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;Wil&#xAD;liam Russell is the Lord Mayor of the City of London and global am&#xAD;bas&#xAD;sador of the UK&#x2019;s fi&#xAD;nan&#xAD;cial and pro&#xAD;fes&#xAD;sional ser&#xAD;vices sec&#xAD;tor.</span>
    </section>

    <p>The United King­dom and Sin­ga­pore are two of the world’s five big­gest ex­porters of fi­nan­cial ser­vices world­wide, and although we are friendly ri­vals, both coun­tries are in­dis­putably im­por­tant pis­tons for the en­gine of global eco­nomic growth as a whole.</p>
    <p>Both of our gov­ern­ments have right­fully spent an un­prece­dented amount of money on sup­port­ing our economies to help us over­come the worst of the pan­demic, but now is the time to take a longer-term view about how we want to re­build.</p>
    <p>So what is our role, as lead­ing in­ter­na­tional fi­nan­cial cen­tres, as we sup­port the re­cov­ery of the global econ­omy? There has to be one pri­or­ity above all oth­ers.</p>
    <p>Ac­cord­ing to the United Na­tions, some US$90 tril­lion (S$125.4 tril­lion) of in­vest­ment will be needed be­tween now and 2030 to achieve global sus­tain­able de­vel­op­ment and cli­mate ob­jec­tives. The con­se­quences of not meet­ing this ob­jec­tive will be se­vere for us all.</p>
    <p>Post-pan­demic, we there­fore have an op­por­tu­nity – a duty – to re-cal­i­brate the global econ­omy to­wards sus­tain­abil­ity. In do­ing so, we will have the blue­print we need to cre­ate the jobs and pros­per­ity that will be so fun­da­men­tal to the suc­cess of our long-term re­cov­ery.</p>
    <p>We have laid some promis­ing foun­da­tions, with both London and Sin­ga­pore con­sis­tently ranked among the best cen­tres in the world for the of­fer of our green fi­nance prod­ucts. Glob­ally, we have al­ready con­trib­uted to a five-fold rise in green bond is­suance since 2015 to more than US$250 bil­lion, while global as­sets un­der man­age­ment in­cor­po­rat­ing en­vi­ron­men­tal, so­cial and gov­er­nance (ESG) man­dates to­tal around US$30.7 tril­lion.</p>
    <p>For the UK’s part, I’m proud of the lead­er­ship we’ve al­ready shown so far. Since 2017, the amount raised in green bonds on the London</p>
    <p>Stock Ex­change has nearly tre­bled to US$29.1 bil­lion, while there are now more than 139 green bonds in to­tal from 18 coun­tries.</p>
    <p>The UK gov­ern­ment is the first G-7 coun­try to leg­is­late for net zero car­bon emis­sions by 2050, while the UK’s re­cently launched Green Fi­nance In­sti­tute will play a fun­da­men­tal role in bring­ing the pri­vate and pub­lic sec­tors to­gether to stim­u­late fur­ther in­no­va­tion.</p>
    <p>The UK’s eco­nomic re­cov­ery will ben­e­fit from the £3 bil­lion (S$5.2 bil­lion) green jobs pack­age an­nounced last week.</p>
    <p>And as the UK looks ahead to the resched­uled COP26 in Glas­gow next year, we know that in Sin­ga­pore, we have a great part­ner in green fi­nance, not only be­cause it’s the right thing to do but also be­cause of the op­por­tu­ni­ties this pro­vides for eco­nomic growth.</p>
    <p>The Mon­e­tary Au­thor­ity of Sin­ga­pore’s an­nounce­ment last Novem­ber of a new US$2 bil­lion green fi­nance in­vest­ment pro­gramme is a ma­jor sign of am­bi­tion, and will mean that ini­tia­tives and in­no­va­tions with a green fo­cus across the Asia-Pa­cific re­gion and be­yond – in­clud­ing the UK – are more likely to get the fi­nan­cial sup­port that they’ll need to flour­ish. This im­pe­tus will cre­ate tens of thou­sands of sus­tain­able jobs both in Sin­ga­pore and across the world, and will ac­cel­er­ate the tran­si­tion to­wards a greener global econ­omy.</p>
    <p>All of this demon­strates a shared be­lief be­tween us that a green fu­ture for fi­nan­cial ser­vices is quickly be­com­ing the only fu­ture, and it’s vi­tal that we work to­gether as ma­jor global fi­nan­cial cen­tres to con­tinue driv­ing that paradig­matic shift. I ex­pect that we will soon reach a point where any in­vest­ment will in­cor­po­rate the best of ESG fac­tors by de­fault, in line with the UN Prin­ci­ples for Re­spon­si­ble In­vest­ment. In do­ing so, we reach a point where only sup­port for a sus­tain­able fu­ture will equate to a fu­ture of eco­nomic growth.</p>


</article>

